 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tcliffdawg>tcliffdawg</A> at: 2/7/03 10:49:19 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCC99><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=christiansons@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>christiansons</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/12/03 2:26:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  sacha's reply</span><hr size=1> I believe the two most influencial characters for Huck were Tom and Jim.  Tom and Huck had fun adventures at the beginning of the novel but as Huck traveled without Tom his adventures became more dangerous and life threatening.  When Huck joins Tom his perspective on life becomes surreal and playful.  Tom brings out the immaturity in Huck and allows him to think of life as an adventure.  The end of the book portrais Huck going back to his immature self as he follows Tom in their adventure to save Jim's life.  Jim also profoundly effects Huck. At the beginning of the novel Huck has some racist ideas ingraved in him by his society yet as he travels with Jim he manages to alter his views.  In the beginning Huck goes along with societies racist view but as he gets to know Jim he sarts making up his own mind about his feeling toward slaves and relies more on his own intelligence.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00CC00><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=muellerd3@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>MuellerD3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/12/03 11:55:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Danny's Response</span><hr size=1>      I believe that the two most influential characters to Huck are Tom and Pap. Tom would be the most influential person to Huck because throughout his entire ordeal Huck thinks about what Tom would do or say about Huck's adventures. Tom taught Huck about having adventures and how they work. it seems that Huck respects Tom more than anyone else. Huck respects Tom because Tom has read a lot and knows about the way things work. Huck and the other boys trust Tom because they figure he knows what he is talking about.<br>
     On the other side of being influenced by people, Huck constantly thinks about Pap as well. Huck probably respects Pap less than anyone else. Pap's influence on Huck is not as great as Tom's because it only comes up in instances. The scene where Huck doesn't find the rider at the circus funny because he is pretending to be drunk. Pap's influence on Huck prevents him from enjoying a potentially fun situation. Tom's influence on Huck is all in fun and harmless and is simply part of childhood. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCC99><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thomsonb3h@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>thomsonb3h</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/12/03 6:57:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  brent's posting</span><hr size=1> I believe that the two most influencial characters on Huck are Pap and Jim. Pap is the most influencial on Huck in the way that he was mean and mistreated Huck. Because Pap mistreated Huck in the scene at the log cabin he forced Huck to run away. After Huck ran away he started a completely different life. If Pap had been good to him who knows where Huck would be right now and who knows how he would have developed. Jim is the second most influencial because he comes into the picture after Pap caused Huck to leave. Jim has many influences on Huck all of which may have been nonexisting or less influencial without the influence pap had on Huck causing him to leave and live the live he is living. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00CC00><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=timms3@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>Timms3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/12/03 9:31:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Stephanie's posting</span><hr size=1> I think that Huck was influenced by mostly Jim and Tom. I feel that Jim influenced Huck because he was the person that made Huck realize that black people are human beings just like white people are. This realization dramatically affects Huck’s outlook on many things. Huck is no longer believes what society has taught him to believe and he is able to think for himself. Jim brings these things out of Huck by showing different emotions such as fear when Huck is lost, anger when Huck tricks him, and longing  when he describes his family. Even though Jim obviously impacted Huck greatly, I think that Tom had an even greater impact. Although Huck learned a lot from Jim most of this knowledge seemed to disappear when Tom showed up. Huck was no longer thinking for himself and living independently. He was just listening to Tom and doing what Tom wanted him to do, no matter how ridiculous it was. This was a major step back for Huck, which is why I believe the person who caused this, Tom, is the person who influenced Huck the most. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCC99><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lambertd3@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>lambertd3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/12/03 9:32:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Daryl's Reply</span><hr size=1>   The two characters who had the most infuence on Huck are Jim and Tom in that order. Jim is the most  influential because he is the main reason Huck is on his adventure.If Jim was not in the book Huck would not have had to run back to the island and tell Jim that slave hunters were coming with dogs, because there would not be any slave huunters coming for him. Further along in the book, Huck was forced to keep on going south in order to prove to Duke and King that Jim was not a runaway slave.Jim also was the reason that Huck ended up with the Phelps's. If Jim had not been turned into the Mr. Phelps, Huck would not have gone to find him and he would not have been reunited with Tom.       <br>
   Tom is the second-most influential character in the novel because does not directly influence Huck's actions like Jim does. Although, he does influence Huck throughout the novel.For instance, the whole time Huck was faking his own death he was thinking what would Tom Sawyer do. In many other of Huck's schemes he also think's about what Tom would do to add more style. Tom influences Huck again when they are going to free Jim by telling Huck how to make a prison escape by the book and he backs it up by saying thast he has read the book so he knows how it is supposed to be done. Still Jim has the most influence on Huck.       <br>
    The scene that influenced Huck the most is when Huck apologizes to Jim for playing a cruel Joke on him. Huck refers back to this scene when he tries to &quot;pray a lie&quot;. He decides to help Jim because Jim said that Huck was his only friend. Therefore Jim influenced Huck the most, followed closely byTom.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00CC00><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=battey4>Battey4</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/13/03 12:29:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Influence</span><hr size=1>       In the second ahlf of this novel, there is much more evidence of where Huck comes from and how he is influenced. I believe that the two characters that influenced Huck the most are Tom and Jim in a close second. The main reason that I would say that Huck is influenced by Tom the most is because Huck refrences what Tom Sawyer would do more than anything. He always considers what Tom would do and how Tom would feel or act in a situation. A reason that it is a good thing that Tom is a influence of Huck is because Tom is a very bright and well read kid. He has a strong system of morals and values, and always keeps Huck in check. <br>
        The reason that a reader would say that Hucky is influenced by Jim would be because of the shift in attitude that Huck has from the begining of the book to the end of the book. In the begining of the book, Huck has absolutely no respect for Jim and believes that he is just a dumb black man, but as Jim and Huck spend more time together Huck realizes that there is more to Jim than just the color of his skin. Jim shows Huck a lot about other pepole and a lot about himself.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCC99><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=urgoa3@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>urgoa3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/13/03 1:42:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  ashley's responce</span><hr size=1> I believe that the two people that influenced Huck the most were Tom and Jim. Tom influenced Huck by showing him how important it was to be looked up at. Huck has always looked up to Tom because of his education strong will and knowledge. Huck is taking after him and wants to be a strong willed person and I think he got it from Tom. The second person that influenced Huck was Jim. Huck comes to love Jim and comes to learn about black people. Jim is Huck's friend and shows him that it is ok not to be racist. Huck grows so much throughout the book because he learns that it is ok to like blacks and to help them.<br>
I think that the most influential part of the book for Huck was when Jim was sold and Huck realized how much he really cared about him and that he wanted to help him. The part of the book when he writes the letter and then rips it up was the most crucial turning point of the book because it is revealed that Huck is not racist.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00CC00><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=urgoa3@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>urgoa3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/13/03 1:53:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  responce to brent</span><hr size=1> I agree with you Brent that Jim influenced Huck and that. I think you have a really good point that Pap was an influence because of how he &quot;forced&quot; Huck to run away and start his life over. I think you are right in the fact that Huck would be completely different if he had never left his father and lived his life on his own. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCC99><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=urgoa3@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>urgoa3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/13/03 2:01:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  responce to Stephanie</span><hr size=1> I agree totally with you Steph. I had the same opinion on the subject. I think that Jim did influence him greatly and you have a wonderful point that all of Huck's knowledge kinda went away after Tom came into his life again. It is weird how much Huck looks up to Tom and does whatever when he is with him. Huck's outlook on Tom doesn't change throughout the whole book. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00CC00><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=morant3@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>MoranT3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/13/03 9:26:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Reply</span><hr size=1> The two characters that are the most influential on Huck are Jim and Pap. Pap plays a huge part in Huck's life because he taught Huck how to cope. Huck learned at an early age how to live by himself, get alone in the wild, and to manipulate people. When the King and Duke come aboard, Huck lets them take over his raft, because he says that they are like Pap. He knows from past experiences that the best thing to do with men like that is just to leave them alone. If Huck had called them in their lies from the second they met, he would never have had all of the experiences with them that he did. Also, Pap made Huck want to get an education, and make something more out of his life. Just seeing how ignorant Pap was, and knowing that Pap didn't want him to make anything of himself was enough for Huck to go to school. Without Pap's influence, Huck wouldn't have had many of the experiences, bad and good, that form his character. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCC99><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=willsont@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>WillsonT</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span>