oes. Jim completely changes how Huck views the black race. Also, Huck would never have been able to have all of the Adventures he had if he didn't have Jim's company. He was lonely after only a few days on the island. Jim's presence made this novel possible. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCC99><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=campbellc4@mrcliffordsenglishclasses>CampbellC4</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/13/03 9:32:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Chelsea's Response</span><hr size=1> &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The two people that influence Huck the greatest are Tom and Jim. Tom is the leader of the pack, he is the most educated of all the boys and every one follows him .Huck listens to what Tom says, and even though he does not agree with what he is saying, he goes a long with it. Of the two, the most influential is Jim.. After Huck’s experiences with Jim, Huck becomes more conscious of how he should treat Jim. Being with Jim and seeing that Jim has feelings and great characteristics Huck realizes that black people are no different from white people. For example, when Huck messes with Jim’s head, Jim is really hurt. Jim had been scared that Huck was in trouble and he was going to risk his life to help him. Huck gradually begins to realize that his tricks aren’t funny and that Jim is a human being. Through Huck’s experiences with Jim he becomes a better person and also begin’s to have more of an independent mind.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The most influential scene is when Huck apologizes to Jim for playing a joke on him. Before being with Jim, Huck had never thought of Jim or any other black man as some one who should be treated with respect or that had feelings.  It showed the transition of racist/sheltered Huck to aware/emotional Huck.<br>
