om/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Who influences Huck the most?</span><hr size=1> I think the two characters that influence Huck the most are Jim and Tom.  I think Jim definitely influences Huck the most and Tom is second.  I think that Tom helps Huck a lot in the book.  When Tom told Huck that he would help him free Jim it was very shocking for Huck.  I think that it helped him to realize that sometimes what's thought of as good and bad in society isn't always right.  It also at least let him know that there was one person on his side on the issue.  I think that Tom also helped Huck to loosen up and have more fun.  When they were getting ready to free Jim what Tom had them do was pointless but I think it took Huck's mind off of whether freeing Jim was right or wrong.  I think that Jim taught Huck to trust his instincts and to worry so much about whether every little thing that he does is okay by society. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00CC00><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=heiskelle3>HeiskellE3</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/13/03 10:01:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=16.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Who influences Huck the most?</span><hr size=1> I think that the scene that affected Huck the most was when Jim told Huck that he was his best and only friend.  This affected Huck so much that even after he decided to turn Jim in he lied to keep him from being caught.  When the  men wanted to come on the raft to check and see if Huck was hiding a slave was a perfect time to turn Jim in but what Jim said 